Record in your journal:

  $ _A diagram of the data flow (can be hand-drawn or digital)_
  - The data flow of task completion is as follows:

              User Terminal Input
                      │
                      ▼
              Commander Argument Parsing
                      │
                      ▼
              cli.js action callback
                      │
                      ▼
              TaskManager.updateTaskStatus()
                      │
                      ▼
              TaskStorage.getTask()
                      │
                      ▼
              Task Entity Retrieved
                      │
                      ▼
              task.markAsDone()
                      │
                      ▼
              Task State Mutated
              (status, completedAt, updatedAt)
                      │
                      ▼
              TaskStorage.save()
                      │
                      ▼
              tasks.json updated
                      │
                      ▼
              CLI success message printed

  $ _The state changes that occur during task completion_
  - When tasks are loaded and retrieved with the call to `TaskStorage.getTask()`, it will have a previous status state such as `todo` or `in_progress`, 
    and after this call, the status will be changed to `done` and this is the state that is persisted to disk.

  $ _Potential points of failure in this process_
  - The call to  TaskStorage.getTask() can cause failure if the taskId passed through the terminal by the user is malformated, or does not exist
  - Another failure would be if the user inputs an unknown status value for example "banana"
  - Another failure might be as a result of calling `save()`, the call does an I/O call, and can result in failures such as disk full, 
    permissions issue, corrupted JSON since there is no try/catch call here.

  $ _How the application persists these changes_
  - The call to `this.storage.save()` within the updateTaskStatus method of `TaskManager` persists the changes to the json file on the filesystem.
